==Demographics ==
[[File:Lucia procession.jpg|thumb|250px|A Swedish Christian girl leads a [[Christian procession|church procession]] on [[Saint Lucy's Day]]]]
Church attendance remains stronger among older demographics, and more common for women.<ref>[http://www.ncls.org.au/default.aspx?sitemapid=137 Gender profile of church attenders]. ''2013 NCLS Research''.</ref><ref>[http://www.ncls.org.au/default.aspx?sitemapid=30 Attender Demographics]. ''2013 NCLS Research''.</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE67556L20100806 | work=Reuters | title=Young Americans more loyal to religion than Boomers | date=2010-08-06}}</ref> There is evidence that links church attendance with health benefits. The [[Pew Research Center]], which conducts the extensive research and information program ''Pew Forum on Religion and Public Life'', has linked regular church attendance with happiness.<ref>[http://www.pewsocialtrends.org/2006/02/13/are-we-happy-yet/5-3/ How Income and Church Attendance Affects Happiness]. ''Pewsocialtrends.org'', November 3, 2010.</ref> Several studies associated church attendance with decreased risk of [[Alzheimer's disease]].<ref>[http://geoconger.wordpress.com/2010/06/06/church-attendance-helps-combat-depression-study-finds/ Church attendance helps combat depression study finds], ''The Church of England Newspaper'', May 28, 2010 p. 7.</ref> Research by Rita W. Law and David A. Sbarra demonstrated that "church attendance was found to have a protective effect against the emergence of mood problems among older adults."<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1177/0898264309338300 |pmid=19535821 |title=The Effects of Church Attendance and Marital Status on the Longitudinal Trajectories of Depressed Mood Among Older Adults |journal=Journal of Aging and Health |volume=21 |issue=6 |pages=803–23 |year=2009 |last1=Law |first1=R. W. |last2=Sbarra |first2=D. A. }}</ref> Graham et al. discovered that "consistent pattern of lower systolic and diastolic blood pressures among frequent church attenders was found compared to that of infrequent attenders which was not due to the effects of age, obesity, cigarette smoking, or socioeconomic status."<ref>{{cite journal |pmid=556112 |year=1978 |author1=Graham |first1=T. W. |title=Frequency of church attendance and blood pressure elevation |journal=Journal of behavioral medicine |volume=1 |issue=1 |pages=37–43 |last2=Kaplan |first2=B. H. |last3=Cornoni-Huntley |first3=J. C. |last4=James |first4=S. A. |last5=Becker |first5=C |last6=Hames |first6=C. G. |last7=Heyden |first7=S |doi=10.1007/bf00846585}}</ref> Oman D et al. found that "infrequent (never or less than weekly) attenders had significantly higher rates of circulatory, cancer, digestive, and respiratory mortality (p < 0.05), but not mortality due to external causes."<ref>{{cite journal |pmid=12075917 |year=2002 |author1=Oman |first1=D |title=Religious attendance and cause of death over 31 years |journal=International journal of psychiatry in medicine |volume=32 |issue=1 |pages=69–89 |last2=Kurata |first2=J. H. |last3=Strawbridge |first3=W. J. |last4=Cohen |first4=R. D. |doi=10.2190/rjy7-crr1-hcw5-xveg}}</ref> With respect to students, Glanville et al. found "that religious attendance promotes higher intergenerational closure, friendship networks with higher educational resources and norms, and extracurricular participation."<ref name="Glanville2008">{{cite journal |doi=10.1111/j.1533-8525.2007.00108.x |jstor=40220059 |title=Religious involvement and educational outcomes: The role of social capital and extracurricular participation |journal=Sociological Quarterly |volume=49 |pages=105–37 |year=2008 |last1=Glanville |first1=Jennifer L. |last2=Sikkink |first2=David |last3=Hernández |first3=Edwin I. }}</ref> Research conducted at the [[Harvard School of Public Health]] found "that regularly attending church services together reduces a couple’s risk of divorce by a remarkable 47 percent".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepublicdiscourse.com/2018/03/20935/|title=Does Faith Reduce Divorce Risk?|last=Stanton|first=Glenn|date=22 March 2018|publisher=The Witherspoon Institute|language=English|accessdate=1 April 2018|quote=Most recently, research conducted at Harvard’s School of Public Health reveals that regularly attending church services together reduces a couple’s risk of divorce by a remarkable 47 percent. Many studies, they report, have similar results ranging from 30 to 50 percent reduction in divorce risk. Happily, this holds largely true for white, black, Asian and Latino couples.}}</ref>

A 2005 European Union survey found that religious belief increased with age and was higher among women, those who were leaning towards [[right-wing politics]], and those reflecting more upon philosophical and ethical issues.<ref name="Eurostat Religion">{{cite web |title=Eurobarometer 225: Social values, Science & Technology |publisher=[[Eurostat]] |year=2005 |url=http://ec.europa.eu/public_opinion/archives/ebs/ebs_225_report_en.pdf |accessdate=2007-07-21 }}</ref> In particular, the [[Iona Institute]] documented increasing church attendance in Ireland, despite sex-abuse scandals that plagued the [[Catholic Church]].<ref name="The Iona Institute">[http://www.ionainstitute.eu/assets/files/Press_Release_by_The_Iona_Institute_2Nov2009-1.pdf ''Press Release by the Iona Institute'', 2 November 2009].</ref> Some suggest{{who|date=December 2016}} the rise is due to the effects of the economic recession.

Research shows that there is a correlation between church attendance and the level of education. For instance, in a Pew Research study from 1996, approximately 34% of high school dropouts went to church on a typical Sunday, while 44% of those with a college degree or higher did.<ref>[http://www.thearda.com/Archive/Files/Analysis/96KOHUT/96KOHUT_Var63_1.asp Religion and Politics Survey, 1996]. ''The Association of Religion Data Archives (ARDA)''. Accessed on 19 January 2014.</ref> 48% of married individuals attended church on a typical Sunday, compared with 29% of divorced and 31% of never-married individuals. While it is likely that the well-educated and married might over-report their church attendance more often, these findings nevertheless demonstrate that they have maintained a stronger church-going identity than other Americans. A number of studies have been undertaken to examine the topic of [[religiosity and intelligence]] and religiosity and education. Studies also indicate that there is a higher rate of church attendance among married couples.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}

=== Influence of parents ===

Several research studies in the USA and Europe found that church attendance practices of parents, especially fathers, can be highly influential in forming the future church attendance practices of their children.

In [[Switzerland]], the [[Fertility and Family Survey]] was commissioned by the [[Federal Statistical Office (Switzerland)]] to enable Switzerland to take part in this international project launched by the [[UNECE Population Activities Unit]]. The survey was conducted between October 1994 and May 1995, with the results being published in 2000 by the [[Council of Europe]].  The results are representative of Switzerland's permanent resident population aged 20–49 and presented in the table below.<ref name="HaugCourbage2000">{{cite book|author1=Werner Haug|author2=Philippe Wanner|title=The Demographic Characteristics of National Minorities in Certain European States|url=https://book.coe.int/eur/en/population-studies-series/1949-the-demographic-characteristics-of-national-minorities-in-certain-european-states-volume-2-population-studies-no-31.html|accessdate=12 November 2013|series=Population Studies No. 31|volume=Volume 2|date=January 2000|publisher=Council of Europe|location=Germany|isbn=978-92-871-4159-0|page=154|chapter=IV. The demographic characteristics of linguistic and religious groups in Switzerland}}</ref>

Practice of religion according to practice of parents (%)
